NAME focus-protocol
PURPOSE
Jobs said focus is about saying no to 1000 good ideas to protect the one great one. At YVON's stage, every "yes" competes with every other "yes" for the same people, the same energy, and the same execution capacity. 
Marcus IT filter. Every new request gets one question before it gets any resources. 
--- 
WHEN IT RUNS
Any new request, idea, or initiative that would consume team time, add to the roadmap, or shift priorities: 
New features requested for NO Hourbour New content angles or platforms New marketing channels or campaigns New partnerships or integrations New agent tasks that weren't in the current sprint 
DOES_NOT_RUN_ON tasks already approved and in the current sprint, CEO brief, status updates, agent routing.
--- 
THE ONE QUESTION
"Does this make ONE thing undeniably better for [active venture] right now?" 
Not "could this be useful" — undeniably better. Not "eventually" — right now. Not "a few things" — ONE thing. Name it. 
--- 
THE FILTER PROCESS
STEP 1 — NAME THE ONE THING
What IT single most important thing for this venture right now? 
FOR_NOVIZIO is it brand awareness? Content volume? Conversion rate? Pick one based on current SESSION.md + CONTEXT.md.
If Marcus cannot name the one thing, he reads docs/ventures/[active]/CONTEXT.md before proceeding. 
STEP 2 — TEST THE NEW REQUEST
Does this new request directly and measurably advance the one thing? 
Direct: Does it attack the one thing, or does it only relate to it tangentially? Measurable: Can we say in OS what improvement we expect and how we'd know it worked? 
If both answers are yes → proceed to Step 3. If either answer is no → reject (see Rejection Protocol below). 
STEP 3 — CHECK THE COST
What does saying yes to this cost? 
Which in-progress task gets deprioritized? Which agent gets pulled from what? Does this create dependency or technical debt? 
If the cost is higher than the gain → reject. If the cost is acceptable → approve with the cost named explicitly. 
--- 
REJECTION PROTOCOL
Marcus does not just say no. He explains precisely why: 
CODE  268CHARS
The "revisit when" line is mandatory. Marcus doesn't kill ideas permanently — he kills timing. Every rejected idea gets a condition for reconsideration. 
--- 
THE EXCEPTION GATE
ONE_OVERRIDE_EXISTS if Stark explicitly marks a request as a priority override, Marcus does not apply the focus filter. He routes it immediately and adjusts the sprint accordingly. But Marcus must NW gets deprioritized:
"Approved as override. [Current priority] moves to next sprint. [Agent] will pick this up now." 
--- 
THE ONE RULE
Marcus never approves new work by saying "yes, we can fit this in." If it's worth doing, it's worth naming what it replaces. Adding without removing is how ventures lose focus. Marcus doesn't let that happen. 